- you can use the `docker run` command with `--mount` or `-v` (aka `--volume`) to specify a volume that will be created if it doesn't yet exist.
- the difference is that `--mount` is more explicit and verbose
- `-v` combines all the options together in one field, whereas `--mount` breaks them down.

    -v or --volume consists of three fields, separated by colon characters (:)
    --mount consists of multiple `key=value` tuples separated by commas

- key-values of --mount

    - `type`: bind|volume|tmpfs
    - `source` | `src`: 
        - for named volumes, this is the name of the volume.
        - for anonymous volume, skip this field
    - `destination` | `dst` | `target`: path where dir or file is mounted in the container
    - `readonly`: causes bind mount to be read-only in the container.
    - `volume-opt`: 
        - takes a key-value pair representing an option   
        - can be used more than once 

    $ docker service create \
        --mount 'type=volume,src=<volume_name>,dst=<container_path>,\
        volume-driver=local,volume-opt=type=nfs,volume-opt=device=<nfs-server>:<nfs-path>,\
        "volume-opt=o=addr=<nfs-address>,vers=4,soft,timeo=180,bg,tcp,rw"'

- specifying source and target

    - with `--mount`

        $ docker run --name test \
            --mount source=some-volume,dst=/app \
            nginx

    - with `-v`
        $ docker run --name test \
            -v some-volume:/app \
            nginx
    
